  "response": "Dash altitude typically refers to the maximum operating altitude of an aircraft. However, the specific altitude can vary significantly depending on the type of aircraft:\n\n1. Civilian Airplanes:\n- Commercial passenger jets typically cruise between 31,000 and 38,000 feet (9.4-11.6 km)\n- Maximum operating altitude is usually around 42,000 feet (12.8 km)\n\n2. Military Airplanes:\n- Fighter jets can reach much higher altitudes\n- Some can operate at 50,000-65,000 feet (15.2-19.8 km)\n- Specialized reconnaissance aircraft like the U-2 can reach up to 70,000 feet (21.3 km)\n\nThe exact dash altitude depends on specific aircraft design, purpose, and technological capabilities. Factors like engine performance, aerodynamics, and pressurization systems influence an aircraft's maximum operating altitude.",
